Trees

4

The Tree ADT

  • A tree is a collection of nodes
  • If it is not empty,
    • then it has a distinguished node r that is the root,
    • and zero or more subtrees that are connected from the root by a directed edge
  • The root of each subtree is a child of r, and r is the parent of each subtree
  • Each subtree is a tree
5

A tree


6

A tree

7

Trees

  • A node can have an arbitrary number of children
  • Nodes with no children are leaves
  • Nodes with the same parent are siblings
8

Paths

  • A path from node n1n1 to node nknk is defined as a sequence of nodes:
    • n1,n2,â€¦,nkn1,n2,â€¦,nk
    • nini is the parent of ni+1ni+1 for iâ‰¤i<kiâ‰¤i<k
  • The length of a path is the number of edges it contains
    • So, the lenght of n1,â€¦,nkn1,â€¦,nk is kâˆ’1kâˆ’1
9

Paths

  • The depth of a node, nini is the length of the path from the root to nini
  • The height of a node, nini is the longest path from nini to a leaf
    • All leaves have height 00
    • The height of the tree is the height of the root
10

Paths

  • If there is a path from nini to njnj then
    • nini is an ancestor of njnj
    • njnj is a descendant of nini
  • If niâ‰ njniâ‰ nj then they are proper, e.g., proper ancestor
11

Example

  • ee is the root
  • There is a path, e,j,qe,j,q from ee to qq of length 2
  • The depth of ii is 1 and the height is 0
  • jj is a proper ancestor of qq

Implementing a tree

  • A tree as an arbitrary number of nodes
  • A node has an arbitrary number of children
    • Can vary greatly, so not a great idea to keep references to all children in the node
  • Left-most child, right sibling (also known as First child, next sibling)
  • Keep two pointers in each node
    • Left child
    • Right sibling

Adding children

from fastcore.basics import patch

@patch
def add_child(self:LCRSNode, key:int) -> LCRSNode:
  if self.left is None:
    self.left = LCRSNode(key)
    return self.left
  else:
    p = self.left
    while p.right is not None:
      p = p.right
    p.right = LCRSNode(key)
    return p.right

Node degree (number of children)

@patch(as_prop=True)
def degree(self:LCRSNode) -> int:
  s, p = 0, self.left
  while p is not None:
    s += 1
    p = p.right
  return s

Getting the nth child

@patch
def __getitem__(self:LCRSNode, key:int) -> LCRSNode:
  c, p = 0, self.left
  while p is not None:
    if c == key:
      return p
    c += 1
    p = p.right
  raise IndexError

Size and height

@patch(as_prop=True)
def size(self:LCRSNode) -> int:
  l, r = 0, 0
  if self.left is not None:
    l = self.left.size
  if self.right is not None:
    r = self.right.size

  return 1 + l + r
33

Size and height

@patch(as_prop=True)
def height(self:LCRSNode) -> int:
  h = 0
  p = self.left
  while p is not None:
    h = max(h, 1 + p.height)
    p = p.right
  return h

Binary trees

  • A binary tree is a tree where each node has at most two children
  • Since only two, each node can hold points to all its children
  • We can reason about height:
    • an average binary tree has height Î˜(nâˆ’âˆ’âˆš)(saysthebook)Î˜(n)(saysthebook)
    • a â€œfullâ€ tree has height âŒˆlog2(n)âŒ‰âˆ’1âŒˆlog2â¡(n)âŒ‰âˆ’1
    • a â€œdegenerateâ€ tree has height nâˆ’1nâˆ’1

A â€œdegenerateâ€ tree

  • A degenerate tree becomes a linked list
  • The height is nâˆ’1nâˆ’1 compared to âŒˆlog2(n+1)âŒ‰âŒˆlog2â¡(n+1)âŒ‰ for a full tree
    • Height of the example is 5
    • If â€œfullâ€, it would be 3
  • Will be important in the future

def inorder(r:BTNode):
    if r is None:
        return ''
    else:
        s = inorder(r.left)
        s += f' {r.key} '  
        s += inorder(r.right)
        return s

Recursive insert

Recursive insert

def lladd(l:LLNode|None, key:int) -> LLNode:
    if l is None:
        return LLNode(key)
    l.nxt = lladd(l.nxt, key)
    return l

Inserting a value

@patch
def _add(self:BST, n:BTNode|None, key:int) -> BTNode|None:
  if n is None:
    return BTNode(key)
    
  if n.key > key:
    n.left = self._add(n.left, key)
  elif n.key < key:
    n.right = self._add(n.right, key)

  return n

What about an iterator?

  • Slightly more complicated
  • We rely on recursive calls to keep track of where we are in the tree
  • and do not have this implicit information in the iterator
  • So, we use a stack to keep track of ancestors
    • Remember, recursive calls uses a stack
62

Inorder iterator

class InorderIter:
  def __init__(self, n:BTNode|None) -> None:
    self.stack = []
    self._pushLCs(n)

  def _pushLCs(self, n:BTNode|None) -> None:
    while n is not None:
      self.stack.append(n)
      n = n.left
63

Inorder iterator

@patch
def __next__(self:InorderIter) -> BTNode:
  if self.stack:
    tmp = self.stack.pop()
  
    if tmp.right is not None:
      self._pushLCs(tmp.right)
  
    return tmp
  else:
    raise StopIteration
64

Inorder iterator

@patch
def __iter__(self:InorderIter) -> InorderIter:
  return self
65

Inorder iterator

@patch
def __iter__(self:BST) -> InorderIter:
  return InorderIter(self.root)

And to check if a value exists

@patch
def _contains(self:BST, n:BTNode|None, key:int) -> bool:
  if n is None:
    return False
    
  if n.key > key:
    return self._contains(n.left, key)
  elif n.key < key:
    return self._contains(n.right, key)
  else: 
    return True

Recursive delete

def lldel(l:LLNode|None, key:int) -> LLNode:
    if l is None:
        return None
    if l.key == key:
        return l.nxt
    else:
        l.nxt = lldel(l.nxt, key)
        return l

Deleting

@patch
def _delete(self:BST, n:BTNode|None, key:int) -> BTNode|None:
  if n is None:
    return None
  if n.key > key:
    n.left = self._delete(n.left, key)
  elif n.key < key:
    n.right = self._delete(n.right, key)
  else:
    if n.right is None:
      return n.left
    if n.left is None:
      return n.right
    n.key = self._min(n.right)
    n.right = self._delete(n.right, n.key)
  return n
79

Finding the smallest node in a subtree

@patch
def _min(self:BST, n:BTNode) -> int:
  if n.left is None:
    return n.key
  else:
    return self._min(n.left)

Computing height

@patch
def _height(self:BST, n:BTNode|None) -> int:
  if n is None:
    return -1
  else:
    return 1 + max(self._height(n.left), \
                   self._height(n.right))

Operations

  • The cost of all operations depends on the height of the tree
  • For balanced trees, all operations are O(logn)O(logâ¡n)
  • For degenerate trees, all operations are O(n)O(n)
  • We know that average trees are rarely balanced or degenerate
  • If we allow deletes, an average tree has height O(nâˆ’âˆ’âˆš)O(n)

AVL-trees

97

AVL-tree

  • Adelson-Velskii and Landis
  • A binary search tree with a balance condition
98

Balance condition

  • Should ensure that the depth of the tree is O(logN)O(logN)
  • Must be easy to maintain
  • First idea, the left and right subtrees should be the same height
    • Can result in poorly balanced trees
99

â€œBalancedâ€ tree

100

Balance conditions

  • Balance at root is not enough
  • So, each node should have left and right subtrees of the same height
    • Would force perfectly balanced trees
    • But too difficult to maintain
101

AVL-trees

  • The heights of the left and right subtrees can differ by at most 1
  • Gives a height of about 1.44â‹…log2(N+2)âˆ’1.3281.44â‹…log2â¡(N+2)âˆ’1.328
    • More than log2log2, but not that much
  • Minimum nodes at at a height
    • S(h)=S(hâˆ’1)+s(hâˆ’2)+1S(h)=S(hâˆ’1)+s(hâˆ’2)+1
  • So, a tree with height 9 has at least 143 nodes

AVL-trees

AVL

Not AVL

103

Implementation

  • Problem: inserting values can destroy the balance
  • So, insert must make sure the tree is balanced after
  • Four possible cases: insert into left (L) subtree of left (L) child, LR, RL, and RR
    • Two are symmetric: LL and RR, and LR and RL
    • And one pair is easier, LL and RR
104

Single rotation (LL and RR)


105

What is going on?

  • Node k2k2 (the root) is violating the balance condition
    • since XX is two levels deeper than ZZ
    • A change to XX caused the violation
  • We can fix this by moving XX higher and YY and ZZ lower
    • This means k1k1 becomes root
    • and k2k2 its right child, since k1<k2k1<k2
    • YY becomes the left child of k2k2 since k1<Y<k2k1<Y<k2
106

Single rotation with numbers

  • Problematic: the subtrees of the root differ by more than 1
  • We need to rotate at the root
  • 2 should become the root and 3 its right child
  • Called a left rotate
107

Single rotation with numbers

  • Left rotate
    • k1k1 is k2.leftk2.left
    • We change k2.leftk2.left to k1.rightk1.right
    • and set k1.rightk1.right to k2k2
108

Single rotation with numbers

    • We change k2.leftk2.left to k1.rightk1.right
    • and set k1.rightk1.right to k2k2

Implementation: Node

@dataclass
class AVLNode:
  key: int
  left: 'AVLNode|None' = None
  right: 'AVLNode|None' = None
  height: int = 0
112

Implementation: AVLTree

class AVLTree:
  def __init__(self) -> None:
    self.root = None
113

Implementation: Add

@patch
def _add(self:AVLTree, n:AVLNode|None, key:int) -> AVLNode:
  if n is None:
    return AVLNode(key)
        
  if n.key > key:
    n.left = self._add(n.left, key)
  elif n.key < key:
    n.right = self._add(n.right, key)

  return self._balance(n)
114

Implementation: Add

@patch
def add(self:AVLTree, key:int) -> None:
  self.root = self._add(self.root, key)
115

Implementation: Balance

@patch
def _balance(self:AVLTree, n:AVLNode|None) -> AVLNode|None:
  if n is None:
    return n

  if self._height(n.left) - self._height(n.right) > 1:
    if self._height(n.left.left) >= self._height(n.left.right):
      n = self._rotate_left(n)
    else:
      n = self._double_left(n)
  elif self._height(n.right) - self._height(n.left) > 1:
    if self._height(n.right.right) >= self._height(n.right.left):
      n = self._rotate_right(n)
    else:
      n = self._double_right(n)

  n.height = max(self._height(n.left), self._height(n.right)) + 1
  return n
116

Implementation: Height

@patch
def _height(self:AVLTree, n:AVLNode|None) -> int:
  if n is None:
    return -1
  return n.height
117

Implementation: Single rotate

@patch
def _rotate_left(self:AVLTree, r2:AVLNode) -> AVLNode:
  r1 = r2.left
  r2.left = r1.right
  r1.right = r2
  r2.height = max(self._height(r2.left), self._height(r2.right)) + 1
  r1.height = max(self._height(r1.left), r2.height) + 1
    
  return r1
118

Implementation: Single rotate

@patch
def _rotate_right(self:AVLTree, r2:AVLNode) -> AVLNode:
  r1 = r2.right
  r2.right = r1.left
  r1.left = r2
  r2.height = max(self._height(r2.left), self._height(r2.right)) + 1
  r1.height = max(self._height(r1.left), r2.height) + 1
    
  return r1

Double rotation

  • Previously, we have seen LL and RR
  • For RL (and LR), we need to rotate twice
    • For RL, a â€œdouble rightâ€
120

Double right

  • A double right means
    • rotate right child left
    • rotate self right
121

Rotate left child right

  • A double right means
    • rotate right child left
    • rotate self right
122

And self right

  • A double right means
    • rotate right child left
    • rotate self right
123

Implementation: rotate double

@patch
def _double_right(self:AVLTree, n:AVLNode) -> AVLNode:
  n.right = self._rotate_left(n.right)
  return self._rotate_right(n)

@patch
def _double_left(self, n:AVLNode) -> AVLNode:
  n.left = self._rotate_right(n.left)
  return self._rotate_left(n)

def _preorder(self:AVLTree, n:AVLNode|None) -> None:
  if n is not None:
    print(n.key)
    self._preorder(n.left)
    self._preorder(n.right)

Random inserts

  • We expect a tree with 1023 nodes to have a height of about 13
    • 1.44â‹…log21023âˆ’1.3281.44â‹…log2â¡1023âˆ’1.328
  • Running a 100 000 inserts, we find that the height is between 10 to 12

    • Compared to a mean of 33.5 with binary search trees and no balancing effort

Oh, deletesâ€¦

@patch
def _delete(self:AVLTree, n:AVLNode|None, key:int) -> AVLNode|None:
  if n is None:
    return None
    
  if n.key > key:
    n.left = self._delete(n.left, key)
  elif n.key < key:
    n.right = self._delete(n.right, key)
  else:
    if n.right is None:
      return n.left
    if n.left is None:
      return n.right
    n.key = self._min(n.right)
    n.right = self._delete(n.right, n.key)
        
  return self._balance(n)

Splay trees

131

Splay trees

  • Many applications have â€œdata localityâ€
    • A node is accessed multiple times within a reasonble timeframe
  • Splay trees push a node to the root after it is accessed
  • Uses a series of rotations from AVL trees
  • Can also help balance the tree
132

Amortized cost

  • Splay trees guarantees that mm consective operations is O(mlog2n)O(mlog2â¡n)
  • A single operation can still be Î˜(n)Î˜(n), so the bound is not O(log2n)O(log2â¡n)
  • This is called amortized running time
    • if mm operations are O(mâ‹…f(n))O(mâ‹…f(n))
    • the amortized cost is O(f(n))O(f(n))
133

Splay trees

  • If an operation is O(n)O(n) and we want O(log2n)O(log2â¡n) it is clear that we must do something to fix it
    • In splay trees, we fix by moving
    • So, if first O(n)O(n), then consecutive close to O(1)O(1)

First idea

  • Single rotation from node to root
  • Will get the node to root
  • Nodes on the path will â€œsufferâ€
    • I.e., move further from the root
  • Î©(mâ‹…n)Î©(mâ‹…n)
  • So, not good enough

Better idea

  • We need to be smarter about our rotations
  • A few cases:
    • X is the node we rotate
    • P is its parent
    • G is its grandparent
141

Better idea

  • If P is the root, then we rotate X and the root
  • If X is a right child and P is a left child, we zig-zag
  • If X and P are both left children, we zig-zig
  • Note the symmetric cases, just as for AVL trees
142

I do not like these namesâ€¦

  • A zig-zig means that the same rotation is performed twice
    • LL or RR
  • A zig-zag means that a rotation followed by the mirror
    • LR or RL
  • Some use zig for one and zag for the other and have four combinations
143

Zig-zig

Zig-zag

145

Splay trees

  • We can move any node to the root by combing zig, zig-zig, and zig-zag
  • We do this each time we search for a node
  • This will ensure that nodes that we have searched for will be closer to the root and be quicker to find again
